Citrus-wood tables are best kept and polished by rubbing with the dry hand, especially just after a bath3 and they are not damaged by spilt wine, as having been created for the purpose of wine- tables.

Few things that supply the apparatus of a more luxurious life rank with this tree, and consequently it seems desirable to dwell on it for a little as well. It was known even to Homer—the Greek name for it being thyon, otherwise ihya. W cll, Homer a has recorded its being burnt among unguents as one of the luxuries of Circe, whom he meant to be understood as a goddess—those who take the word thyon to mean perfumes being greatly in error, especially as in the same verse he says that cedar and larch were burnt at the same time, which shows that he was only speaking of trees.
